<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/179847-does-this-book-every-become-as-religiously">Does this book every become as religiously controversial or employ opinion? So far it appears to only be using reason and logic. Is this where the controversy lies?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_179847'><a id="like_count_community_question_179847" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/179847?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">4 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F8520362-the-grand-design">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/179847-does-this-book-every-become-as-religiously">6 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/179847-does-this-book-every-become-as-religiously">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/41704957-ben-mcdonald"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1427739132i/41704957._UX100_CR0,18,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/41704957-ben-mcdonald">Ben McDonald</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">in a word, yes. one of the main ideas in the book is &apos;M-theory.&apos; A theory of everything, a single equation that maps out and explains the whole of exi<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">in a word, yes. one of the main ideas in the book is 'M-theory.' A theory of everything, a single equation that maps out and explains the whole of existance. it's logical to accept such a thing exists. but the religious contrevercy occurs when you apply this logic: if M-theory is reolised then there will be no need for a god to map out and explain the whole of existance. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
